A **"lame duck"** in congressional politics refers to an elected official who is serving the remainder of their term after losing re-election or failing to secure re-nomination. These officials often have reduced influence because they no longer face the pressure of future elections. In this context, the lame-duck Democrats—having lost their seats—were seen as more pliable for securing votes on the Thirteenth Amendment.}
